TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

@func = ("\ln{(x)}","\log{(x)}","\ln{(-x)}","\log{(-x)}");
@pick = shuffle(2);
$f[0] = $func[$pick[0]];
$f[1] = $func[$pick[1]+2];
$ans1 = "INFINITY";
$ans2 = "-INFINITY";


BEGIN_TEXT

Find the value of each limit below.  If the limit goes to \( \infty \) or \( - \infty \), enter ${BITALIC}INFINITY${EITALIC} or ${BITALIC}-INFINITY${EITALIC}, respectively.
$BR
$BR
(a) As \( \displaystyle x \longrightarrow 0^+,\  - $f[0] \longrightarrow \) \{ ans_rule(15) \}

$BR
$BR
(b) As \( \displaystyle x \longrightarrow 0^-,\  $f[1] \longrightarrow \) \{ ans_rule(15) \}


END_TEXT

ANS(Compute("$ans1")->cmp() );
ANS(Compute("$ans2")->cmp() );


#ANS(fun_cmp( $ans1, vars=>['I','N','F','T','Y']) );
#ANS(fun_cmp( $ans2, vars=>['I','N','F','T','Y']) );

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
a) Since \( - $f[0] \) becomes more and more positive as \( x \) decreases to 0 from the right, as \( \displaystyle \ \ x \longrightarrow 0^+,\  -$f[0] \longrightarrow \infty \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) Since \( $f[1] \) becomes more and more negative as \( x \) increases to 0 from the left, as \( \displaystyle \ \ x \longrightarrow 0^-,\  $f[1] \longrightarrow - \infty \).
$BR
END_SOLUTION
      

